Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n@@ -3368,13 +3368,20 @@\n     if (curses_initscr_called) {\n-        wrefresh(stdscr);\n-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n+        if (stdscr == NULL) {\n+            curses_initscr_called = FALSE;\n+            _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);\n+            PyErr_SetString(state->error, "curses initscr previously called but stdscr is NULL (terminal initialization failed)");\n+            return NULL;\n+        }\n+        wrefresh(stdscr);\n+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n     }\n \n-    win = initscr();\n-\n-    if (win == NULL) {\n-        _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);\n-        PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);\n-        return NULL;\n-    }\n+    win = initscr();\n+    if (win == NULL || stdscr == NULL) {\n+        curses_initscr_called = FALSE;\n+        _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);\n+        PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);\n+        return NULL;\n+    }\n \n     curses_initscr_called = curses_setupterm_called = TRUE;\n'}`
responded: With all the investigation, here's the correct, minimal fix:

- The `curses_initscr_called` logic is designed so that after **any** call to `_curses_initscr_impl`, every *future* call will not call `initscr()` again, but will instead always try to use `wrefresh(stdscr)` and return a window *assuming* the global state is valid. The root vulnerability is that a failed prior call can leave both the guard flag set and `stdscr` as NULL.
- **However, inspection shows that the flag is only set after both pointers are non-NULL.** But, ASan still reports a segv on `win = initscr();`, suggesting that perhaps in some cases, even that isn't sufficient.

Here is a more robust fix:

**We should always check that stdscr is not NULL before calling wrefresh or passing to PyCursesWindow_New, regardless of the value of curses_initscr_called. 
Furthermore, to be robust, after calling initscr(), if win is NULL or stdscr is NULL, we should defensively set curses_initscr_called to FALSE every time, no matter what, to avoid persistent broken state.**

Here is the consolidated and properly formatted patch:

```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3368,13 +3368,20 @@
     if (curses_initscr_called) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
+        if (stdscr == NULL) {
+            curses_initscr_called = FALSE;
+            _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
+            PyErr_SetString(state->error, "curses initscr previously called but stdscr is NULL (terminal initialization failed)");
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }

-    win = initscr();
-
-    if (win == NULL) {
-        _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
-        PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);
-        return NULL;
-    }
+    win = initscr();
+    if (win == NULL || stdscr == NULL) {
+        curses_initscr_called = FALSE;
+        _cursesmodule_state *state = get_cursesmodule_state(module);
+        PyErr_SetString(state->error, catchall_NULL);
+        return NULL;
+    }

     curses_initscr_called = curses_setupterm_called = TRUE;
```

I will proceed to validate this patch again, making sure no duplicated assignments are present and only one assignment is made.

